Thamnomanes is a genus of insectivorous birds in the antbird family, Thamnophilidae. They are restricted to the Neotropics and are important components of forest mixed-species feeding flocks.
The genus Thamnomanes was introduced by the German ornithologist Jean Cabanis in 1847. The name combines the Ancient Greek words thamnos "bush" and -manÄ“s "fond of". The type species was subsequently designated as the cinereous antshrike.This genus contains the following species:
Dusky-throated antshrike, Thamnomanes ardesiacus
Cinereous antshrike, Thamnomanes caesius
Saturnine antshrike, Thamnomanes saturninus
Bluish-slate antshrike, Thamnomanes schistogynus